	directAnswerHtml={`<strong style="color: var(--color-ink);">If you serve on a church staff, the Father’s Heart Bible™ is for you.</strong> You are the executive or associate pastor, the worship and production tech, the kids or student director, the office and admin manager, the communications and media lead, the finance and bookkeeping hand, the facilities crew, the groups and discipleship coordinator, the care and counseling team, the missions and outreach organizer, the first-impressions and hospitality host. You keep the whole thing running — mostly unseen, often measured only by tasks. The <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Father’s Heart Bible™</a> is a fresh English translation you can read and <em>listen to</em> free on any phone — and it reveals the God you serve as <em>Father</em>, from Genesis to Revelation. Whether you’re searching for “Bible verses for church staff,” “encouragement for ministry workers,” or a way through ministry burnout, it begins in one place: before you are a job description, you are a beloved child.`}
	keyTakeaway={`You are not the help — you are a son or daughter. The God you set up chairs for, balance budgets for, and run slides for sees the work no one else sees, and He is after you long before He is after your tasks.`}
	painsHeading={`The weight church staff carry`}
	painsIntroHtml={`Behind every smooth Sunday is a staff that arrived hours early and left long after — people who carry the building, the budget, the database, and a hundred small fires no one ever notices. The pay is modest, the hours are long, the help is thin, and the thank-you is rare. Over time a quiet ache sets in: <em>am I valued here, or only useful?</em>`}
	painStats={[
		{ value: `54%`, label: `of ministry leaders say they often feel their work is unappreciated` },
		{ value: `70%+`, label: `report working more than 50 hours in a typical week` },
		{ value: `60%`, label: `feel overwhelmed and unable to meet the demands of church and family` },
		{ value: `66%`, label: `feel they lack sufficient support from the people they serve` },
		{ value: `29%`, label: `feel they have no one to confide in about their stress` },
		{ value: `~40%`, label: `of ministry leaders are at high risk of burnout — and the staff who serve quietly are often the last to be cared for` },
	]}
	painsBodyHtml={`<p>Low pay, long hours, too few hands, and too little recognition are not just management problems — they wear on the soul. The person who keeps everyone else organized often has no one organizing care for <em>them</em>. The one who makes the church feel welcoming can quietly feel invisible inside it. And because it’s “ministry,” the exhaustion comes wrapped in guilt, as if being tired meant loving Jesus less.</p><p>These are not signs of a weak calling or a small faith. They are the symptoms of a son or daughter who has been pouring out without being filled — measured by tasks when they were made for a Father’s delight. There is a Father who sees every unseen hour, and who is after the person long before the performance.</p>`}
	painsSources={[
		{ label: `Barna — pastoral flourishing & overwork`, url: `https://www.barna.com/trends/pastoral-flourishing/` },
