	offersBlocks={[
		{ heading: `Eyes that see the unseen`, bodyHtml: `The work no one thanked you for, your Father <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read/hebrews/6" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">has not overlooked</a>. He is not unjust; nothing done in love for His name is forgotten by Him.` },
		{ heading: `Rest for the laborer`, bodyHtml: `To the one who sets up everyone else’s rest, Jesus says <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read/matthew/11" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">“come to Me… and I will give you rest.”</a> You were never meant to be the source — only a child who drinks first.` },
		{ heading: `Worth beyond the task list`, bodyHtml: `When the title and the to-dos are stripped away, you are still His <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read/colossians/3" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">beloved child</a>, working for a Father and not for men. Your worth is your sonship, not your productivity.` },
		{ heading: `The one thing necessary`, bodyHtml: `Busy with much serving, you are gently told <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read/luke/10" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">one thing is necessary</a> — to sit at His feet. Being with the Father is the portion no reorg can take from you.` },
	]}
	whyHeading={`Why the Father's Heart Bible™ for church staff`}
	whyBlocks={[
		{ heading: `You meet the God you serve — as Father`, bodyHtml: `Every other Bible names Him “God.” The Father’s Heart Bible™ reveals Him as <em>Father</em> wherever Scripture does — from <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read/genesis/1" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Genesis 1</a> onward. When the One you work for has a Father’s face, your service becomes communion before it becomes a checklist.` },
		{ heading: `It refills the one who keeps things running`, bodyHtml: `Free to <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">read online</a> with audio on every chapter, it’s built for the staff member’s real week — come to be fathered before the inbox opens, and let Scripture feed <em>you</em> before you serve anyone else.` },
		{ heading: `From measured to beloved`, bodyHtml: `The pressure of being measured by tasks fades when you remember whose you are. Reading the Word in the Father’s own voice keeps your identity anchored — start with our <a href="/guides/how-to-pray/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">how-to-pray guide</a> or the <a href="/verses/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">verses by topic</a>.` },
	]}
	voicesHeading={`The Father’s heart, in their words`}
	voicesIntroHtml={`Beneath every unseen task is the truth these voices lived by — that God is a near and tender Father:`}
	voices={[
		{ quote: `Answered prayer is the interchange of love between the Father and His child.`, name: `Andrew Murray`, role: `who taught a generation to live as the Father’s children`, photo: `https://cdn.sanity.io/images/rusi1hyi/production/133bc45cfa954cf1ae99b7afac5954eca764ed70-500x830.jpg` },
		{ quote: `God tenderly invites us to believe that He is our true Father and we are His true children.`, name: `Martin Luther`, role: `the Reformer, on the opening words of the Lord’s Prayer`, photo: `https://cdn.sanity.io/images/rusi1hyi/production/b205722e3e040337b10b11b66e159abd8623472e-500x791.jpg` },
		{ quote: `There is heaven in the depth of that word — Father.`, name: `Charles Spurgeon`, role: `the “Prince of Preachers”`, photo: `https://cdn.sanity.io/images/rusi1hyi/production/e48a128da123135241be9c95cf35b37498d94ea5-500x617.jpg` },
	]}
	voicesCreditHtml={`Photos via <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Wikimedia Commons</a> &mdash; Andrew Murray, Martin Luther, and Charles Spurgeon (all public domain).`}
	wordHeading={`His Word will not return void`}
	wordBodyHtml={`<p>When our Father said, “Let there be light,” there was light. His Word does what He sends it to do. The same Word you serve every week — printing it, projecting it, scheduling it — will not come back empty, and not least in <em>you</em>.</p><p class="mt-4" style="color: var(--color-ink);">“My word… will not return to me empty, but will accomplish that which I purpose.” <span style="color: var(--color-muted);">— Isaiah 55:11</span></p>`}
	fatherSaysHeading={`What the Father says over you`}
	fatherSaysHtml={`<p>“Beloved, I see it all — the early arrivals, the late nights, the things you fixed that no one noticed were ever broken. You are not My hired help; you are My child. I did not draw you near because I needed a worker — I drew you near because I love you, and I wanted you close.</p><p>Put down the list for a moment. Your worth was never your output, and My delight in you does not rise and fall with the budget or the attendance. Let Me refill what the long weeks have drained. Let Me thank you where no committee did. Then go and serve — not to be valued, but because you already are. I am your Father, and you are Mine, and nothing you do for Me is ever forgotten.”</p>`}
	prayerHeading={`A prayer for church staff`}
	prayerHtml={`<p>Our Father, we thank You and praise You for all church staff — the ones who keep the whole church running, who carry the building, the budget, and a hundred unseen fires no one ever thanks them for. Let them hear Your whisper above every task list and every demand. Let them encounter Your love — not as a job they perform, but as a weight they feel — and experience Your delight over them, apart from any deadline, any metric, any Sunday.</p><p>Give them grace to prioritize intimacy with You above their productivity, and to receive their identity as Your sons and daughters before their role on the staff page. Father, would You see the unseen ones — provide for what their pay does not cover, send help where they are stretched thin, and let them feel valued, not merely useful.</p><p>I pray Your protection over them from the enemy, from temptation, from bitterness and resentment when they go unappreciated, and from despair. Let them know there is no condemnation in You — that being tired does not mean they love You less. Let them know You, their Father, as their true inheritance and reward, for every other gift pales beside the gift of You. And may they wake up every single day under the pour of their heavenly Father’s heart for them.</p><p>In Jesus’ name, amen.</p>`}
